## Public Perception and Policy Implications

Surveys in the United States reveal that a majority of Americans recognize the increasing threat of natural disasters intensified by climate change and support government adaptation policies, especially when framed in the context of climate change impacts. Support is higher among those who believe in climate change and perceive it as a threat to future generations. People of color and lower-income groups show greater support for adaptation efforts, reflecting their heightened vulnerability ([Resources for the Future, 2020](https://www.rff.org)).

## Conclusion and Opinion

The evidence unequivocally indicates that climate change is intensifying many types of natural disasters through well-understood physical mechanisms. While some uncertainties remain, particularly regarding regional flood trends and tropical cyclone frequency, the overall trend points to increased risks and damages from heatwaves, wildfires, droughts, heavy precipitation, and intense tropical storms.

Given the substantial human and economic costs associated with these disasters, it is imperative that policymakers prioritize both mitigation of greenhouse gas emissions and adaptation strategies to enhance resilience. Public support for such measures is strong when the connection to climate change is clearly communicated.

In my assessment, the scientific consensus and observed data compel urgent action to address climate change as a driver of natural disasters. Ignoring this link risks exacerbating vulnerabilities and undermining sustainable development globally.

